Morrison v. Dodge. Neither the documentary evidence specified in the bill of exceptions, nor any brief of the same, being set out and authenticated, either in the bill of exceptions or in the transcript of the record, and it not appearing that said evidence ever was briefed and approved by the judge so as to become a part of the re,cord, and none of the *731errors assigned being susceptible of proper examination and adjudication without considering the evidence, no reversal of the judgment of the court below is legally possible. April 30, 1894.

Argued at the last term.

R. R. Norman and W. L. Clarke, by D. W. Rountree, for plaintiff in error. DeLacy & Bishop, contra.

Judgment affirmed.
